---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { withBase } from '@/lib/withBase';
import PageHeader from '@/components/ui/PageHeader.astro';
import BitField from '@/components/react/BitField.tsx';
import ValueTable from '@/components/ui/ValueTable.astro';
import Formula from '@/components/ui/Formula.astro';
import Callout from '@/components/ui/Callout.astro';
import DocRef from '@/components/ui/DocRef.astro';
import { DSM_PKR } from '@/data/fields';
import { NB_DP_TABLE, NPKT_TABLE, MID_TABLE } from '@/data/tables';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="DSM-PKR"
  description="DSM-PKR: how OSNMA delivers and authenticates a public key over the signal."
>
  <PageHeader
    eyebrow="3 · Data structures"
    title="DSM-PKR: public key renewal"
    lead="The message that hands a receiver a public key over the air, carrying just enough of the Merkle tree to prove the key is genuine."
  />

  <p>
    Before a receiver can trust a signed KROOT, it needs the public key that signed
    it. The <strong>DSM-PKR</strong> delivers that key in the signal
    <DocRef doc="icd" section="3.2.2" />. Rather than ship a heavyweight
    certificate, it carries the key as one <em>leaf</em> of the Merkle tree plus the
    four sibling nodes needed to climb to the root the receiver already trusts.
  </p>

  <h2>The layout</h2>
  <p>Select a field to see what it carries:</p>

  <BitField spec={DSM_PKR} client:visible />

  <h2>From key to leaf</h2>
  <p>
    The public key does not sit in the tree on its own. It is wrapped with a type
    and an identifier to form the Merkle leaf:
  </p>
  <Formula tex="m_i = \text{NPKT} \,\|\, \text{NPKID} \,\|\, \text{NPK}" display />
  <p>
    <strong>NPKT</strong> says what kind of key it is (ECDSA P-256, P-521, or an
    alert message), <strong>NPKID</strong> identifies it, and <strong>NPK</strong>
    is the compressed key itself. The receiver hashes this leaf and works upward.
  </p>
  <ValueTable table={NPKT_TABLE} />

  <h2>Which leaf, and which siblings</h2>
  <p>
    The <strong>MID</strong> field names which of the sixteen leaves is being
    delivered, and therefore which four sibling nodes travel with it in the
    <strong>ITN</strong> (Intermediate Tree Nodes) field — four 256-bit hashes, one
    per tree level <DocRef doc="icd" section="3.2.2.2 / 3.2.2.3" />.
  </p>
  <ValueTable table={MID_TABLE} />

  <h2>Size and delivery</h2>
  <p>
    The <strong>NB_DP</strong> field fixes how many 104-bit blocks the DSM-PKR
    spans, and therefore its total length.
  </p>
  <ValueTable table={NB_DP_TABLE} />
  <p>
    Like every DSM, a DSM-PKR is reassembled from blocks carried in the HKROOT
    stream. Its blocks must all arrive within a 13-hour reception window or the
    partial message is discarded <DocRef doc="rxg" section="3.2" />.
  </p>

  <Callout type="note">
    <p>
      The receiver authenticates the key by recomputing the Merkle root from the
      leaf and the carried siblings and comparing it to the root it holds. Watch
      that climb run on real test-vector data in the
      <a href={withBase('/machinery/merkle-tree')}>Merkle tree explorer</a>.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <div class="level-engineer">
    <h3>Padding</h3>
    <p>
      A trailing <strong>P_DP</strong> field pads the message up to a whole number
      of 104-bit blocks. Its content is a hash of the tree root and the leaf, so it
      carries no secret and simply fills the last block.
    </p>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
